{"title_page": "Paul May", "text_new": "{{short description|German film director}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image       =\n| name        = Paul May\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|1909|5|8|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Munich]], Germany\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|1976|2|25|1909|5|8|df=yes}}\n| death_place = [[Taufkirchen (bei M\u00fcnchen)|Taufkirchen]], Germany\n| occupation  = Film director<br>Film editor\n| yearsactive = 1935-1972\n}}\n\n'''Paul May''' (8 May 1909 &ndash; 25 February 1976) was a German [[film director]] and [[film editor|editor]]. He directed 40 films between 1935 and 1972.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.filmportal.de/person/paul-may_d3f869c92d5b4da29a452aec68279ad9 |title=Paul May |work=Film Portal |accessdate=29 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nHe was the son of [[Peter Ostermayr]], a film producer with [[Universum Film AG]], and his wife Olga, ''n\u00e9e'' Wernhard. After secondary school in [[Feldkirch, Vorarlberg|Feldkirch]], he entered to film industry and trained in [[film laboratory]] work. He became a [[Film editing|film editor]] in 1930 and [[assistant director]] in 1935. His first film as director was ''Edelwei\u00dfk\u00f6nig'', in 1938.\n\nAfter the Second World War, he adopted the pseudonym Paul May. His greatest successes were ''[[08/15 (1954 film)|08/15]]'' (1954), ''[[The Forests Sing Forever]]'' (1959), ''[[Via Mala (1961 film)|Via Mala]]'' (1961) from the book by [[John Knittel]], and ''[[Scotland Yard Hunts Dr. Mabuse]]'' (1963) with [[Peter van Eyck]]. He also directed for television. He directed more than forty films between 1935 and 1972.\n\n==Selected filmography==\n===Editor===\n{{div col|colwidth=28em}}\n* ''[[Panic in Chicago]]'' (1931)\n* ''[[Shooting Festival in Schilda]]'' (1931)\n* ''[[The Spanish Fly (1931 film)|The Spanish Fly]]'' (1931)\n* ''[[The Champion Shot]]'' (1932)\n* ''[[Secret of the Blue Room (1932 film)|Secret of the Blue Room]]'' (1932)\n* ''[[The Peak Scaler]]'' (1933)\n* ''[[William Tell (1934 film)|William Tell]]'' (1934)\n* ''[[ Holiday From Myself (1934 film)| Holiday From Myself]]'' (1934)\n* ''[[The Four Musketeers (1934 film)|The Four Musketeers]]'' (1934)\n*''[[Peter, Paul and Nanette]]'' (1935)\n* ''[[Home Guardsman Bruggler]]'' (1936)\n* ''[[The Hunter of Fall (1936 film)|The Hunter of Fall]]'' (1936)\n* ''[[Triad (film)|Triad]]'' (1938)\n* ''[[Frau Sixta]]'' (1938)\n* ''[[Storms in May]]'' (1938)\n{{div col end}}\n===Screenwriter===\n* ''[[ Night of the Twelve]]'' (1949)\n===Director===\n'''Film'''\n{{div col|colwidth=28em}}\n*1939: ''Der Edelwei\u00dfk\u00f6nig''\n*1939: ''Waldrausch ''\n*1940: ''[[Beates Flitterwoche]] / Sonderbare Flitterwochen''\n*1940: ''[[Left of the Isar, Right of the Spree (1940 film)|Left of the Isar, Right of the Spree]]''\n*1942: ''[[Violanta (1942 film)|Violanta]]'' (also co-script)\n*1943: ''Die unheimliche Wandlung des Alex Roscher''\n*1949: ''[[Duel with Death]]'' (also script); Prod. [[G. W. Pabst]]\n*1950: ''[[King for One Night]]'' (also producer)\n*1952: ''[[Two People (1952 film)|Two People]]''\n*1953: ''[[Young Heart Full of Love]]''\n*1954: ''[[08/15 (1954 film)|08/15]]''\n*1954: ''[[The Phantom of the Big Tent]]''\n*1955: ''[[Doctor Solm]]'' \n*1955: ''[[08/15 Zweiter Teil|08/15 \u2013 Im Krieg]]''\n*1955: ''[[08/15 in der Heimat|08/15 \u2013 In der Heimat]]''\n*1956: ''Weil du arm bist, mu\u00dft du fr\u00fcher sterben''\n*1957: ''[[Wei\u00dfer Holunder]]'' \n*1957: ''Flucht in die Tropennacht''\n*1957: ''[[The Fox of Paris]]'' \n*1958: ''{{Interlanguage link multi|Die Land\u00e4rztin (film)|de|3=Die Land\u00e4rztin (Film)|lt=Die Land\u00e4rztin}}''\n*1959: ''[[The Forests Sing Forever]]''\n*1959: ''Heimat, deine Lieder'' \n*1960: ''Der Schleier fiel''\n*1960: ''Soldatensender Calais'' \n*1961: ''[[Via Mala (1961 film)|Via Mala]]''\n*1961: ''[[Freddy and the Millionaire]]''\n*1962: ''[[Waldrausch (1962 film)|Waldrausch]]''\n*1963: ''Barras heute''\n*1963: ''[[Scotland Yard Hunts Dr. Mabuse]]''\n*1967: ''{{Interlanguage link multi|Mittsommernacht|de|3=Mittsommernacht (1967)|lt=Mittsommernacht}}'' \n{{div col end}}\n'''Television'''\n*1964: ''Die Truhe'' \u2014 (based on a play by James Liggat and Alan Reeve-Jones)\n*1965: ''[[Die Schl\u00fcssel (miniseries)|Die Schl\u00fcssel]]'' (TV miniseries) \u2014 (remake of [[Francis Durbridge]]'s ''The Desperate People'', 1963)\n*1965: ''Gl\u00fcck in Frankreich'' \u2014 (based on a story by [[Ernst von Salomon]])\n*1965: ''Acht Stunden Zeit'' \u2014 (based on a play by Charles Ma\u00eetre)\n*1966: ''{{Interlanguage link multi|Melissa (German miniseries)|de|3=Melissa (1966)|lt=Melissa}}'' (TV miniseries) \u2014 (remake of [[Francis Durbridge]]'s ''Melissa'', 1964)\n*1967: ''In Sachen Erzberger gegen Helfferich'' \u2014 (screenplay by [[Axel Eggebrecht]])\n*1967\u20131968: ''[[Sherlock Holmes (1967 TV series)|Sherlock Holmes]]'' (TV series) \u2014 (remake of ''[[Sherlock Holmes (1965 TV series)|Sherlock Holmes]]'', 1965)\n*1968: ''Eine Gefangene bei Stalin und Hitler'' \u2014 (based on ''Under Two Dictators'' by [[Margarete Buber-Neumann]])\n*1969\u20131972: ''[[K\u00f6niglich Bayerisches Amtsgericht]]'' (TV series, 7 episodes)\n*1969: ''Nennen Sie mich Alex'' \u2014 (film about [[Oleg Penkovsky]])\n*1970: ''Theatergarderobe'' (TV series)\n*1971: ''Die Schrott-Story''\n*1971\u20131972: ''F\u00fcnf Tage hat die Woche'' (TV series)\n*1972: ''Nicht Lob \u2013 noch Furcht. Graf Galen, Bischof von M\u00fcnster'' \u2014 (screenplay by [[Luise Rinser]])\n*1972\u20131975: ''{{Ill|Im Auftrag von Madame|de}}'' (TV series, 32 episodes)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0003904|Paul May}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:May, Paul}}\n[[Category:1909 births]]\n[[Category:1976 deaths]]\n[[Category:German television directors]]\n[[Category:German film directors]]\n[[Category:German-language film directors]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|German film director}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image       =\n| name        = Paul May\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|1909|5|8|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Munich]], Germany\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|1976|2|25|1909|5|8|df=yes}}\n| death_place = [[Taufkirchen (bei M\u00fcnchen)|Taufkirchen]], Germany\n| occupation  = Film director<br>Film editor\n| yearsactive = 1935-1972\n}}\n\n'''Paul May''' (8 May 1909 &ndash; 25 February 1976) was a German [[film director]] and [[film editor|editor]]. He directed 40 films between 1935 and 1972.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.filmportal.de/person/paul-may_d3f869c92d5b4da29a452aec68279ad9 |title=Paul May |work=Film Portal |accessdate=29 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nHe was the son of [[Peter Ostermayr]], a film producer with [[Universum Film AG]], and his wife Olga, ''n\u00e9e'' Wernhard. After secondary school in [[Feldkirch, Vorarlberg|Feldkirch]], he entered to film industry and trained in [[film laboratory]] work. He became a [[Film editing|film editor]] in 1930 and [[assistant director]] in 1935. His first film as director was ''Edelwei\u00dfk\u00f6nig'', in 1938.\n\nAfter the Second World War, he adopted the pseudonym Paul May. His greatest successes were ''[[08/15 (1954 film)|08/15]]'' (1954), ''[[The Forests Sing Forever]]'' (1959), ''[[Via Mala (1961 film)|Via Mala]]'' (1961) from the book by [[John Knittel]], and ''[[Scotland Yard Hunts Dr. Mabuse]]'' (1963) with [[Peter van Eyck]]. He also directed for television. He directed more than forty films between 1935 and 1972.\n\n==Selected filmography==\n===Editor===\n{{div col|colwidth=28em}}\n* ''[[Panic in Chicago]]'' (1931)\n* ''[[Shooting Festival in Schilda]]'' (1931)\n* ''[[The Spanish Fly (1931 film)|The Spanish Fly]]'' (1931)\n* ''[[The Champion Shot]]'' (1932)\n* ''[[Secret of the Blue Room (1932 film)|Secret of the Blue Room]]'' (1932)\n* ''[[The Peak Scaler]]'' (1933)\n* ''[[William Tell (1934 film)|William Tell]]'' (1934)\n* ''[[ Holiday From Myself (1934 film)| Holiday From Myself]]'' (1934)\n* ''[[The Four Musketeers (1934 film)|The Four Musketeers]]'' (1934)\n*''[[Peter, Paul and Nanette]]'' (1935)\n* ''[[Home Guardsman Bruggler]]'' (1936)\n* ''[[The Hunter of Fall (1936 film)|The Hunter of Fall]]'' (1936)\n* ''[[Triad (film)|Triad]]'' (1938)\n* ''[[Frau Sixta]]'' (1938)\n* ''[[Storms in May]]'' (1938)\n{{div col end}}\n===Screenwriter===\n* ''[[ Night of the Twelve]]'' (1949)\n===Director===\n'''Film'''\n{{div col|colwidth=28em}}\n*1939: ''Der Edelwei\u00dfk\u00f6nig''\n*1939: ''Waldrausch ''\n*1940: ''[[Beates Flitterwoche]] / Sonderbare Flitterwochen''\n*1940: ''[[Left of the Isar, Right of the Spree (1940 film)|Left of the Isar, Right of the Spree]]''\n*1942: ''[[Violanta (1942 film)|Violanta]]'' (also co-script)\n*1943: ''Die unheimliche Wandlung des Alex Roscher''\n*1949: ''[[Duel with Death]]'' (also script); Prod. [[G. W. Pabst]]\n*1950: ''[[King for One Night]]'' (also producer)\n*1952: ''[[Two People (1952 film)|Two People]]''\n*1953: ''[[Young Heart Full of Love]]''\n*1954: ''[[08/15 (1954 film)|08/15]]''\n*1954: ''[[The Phantom of the Big Tent]]''\n*1955: ''[[Doctor Solm]]'' \n*1955: ''[[08/15 Zweiter Teil|08/15 \u2013 Im Krieg]]''\n*1955: ''[[08/15 in der Heimat|08/15 \u2013 In der Heimat]]''\n*1956: ''Weil du arm bist, mu\u00dft du fr\u00fcher sterben''\n*1957: ''[[Wei\u00dfer Holunder]]'' \n*1957: ''Flucht in die Tropennacht''\n*1957: ''[[The Fox of Paris]]'' \n*1958: ''{{Interlanguage link multi|Die Land\u00e4rztin (film)|de|3=Die Land\u00e4rztin (Film)|lt=Die Land\u00e4rztin}}''\n*1959: ''[[The Forests Sing Forever]]''\n*1959: ''Heimat, deine Lieder'' \n*1960: ''Der Schleier fiel''\n*1960: ''Soldatensender Calais'' \n*1961: ''[[Via Mala (1961 film)|Via Mala]]''\n*1961: ''[[Freddy and the Millionaire]]''\n*1962: ''[[Waldrausch (1962 film)|Waldrausch]]''\n*1963: ''Barras heute''\n*1963: ''[[Scotland Yard Hunts Dr. Mabuse]]''\n*1967: ''{{Interlanguage link multi|Mittsommernacht|de|3=Mittsommernacht (1967)|lt=Mittsommernacht}}'' \n{{div col end}}\n'''Television'''\n*1964: ''Die Truhe'' \u2014 (based on a play by James Liggat and Alan Reeve-Jones)\n*1965: ''[[Die Schl\u00fcssel (miniseries)|Die Schl\u00fcssel]]'' (TV miniseries) \u2014 (remake of [[Francis Durbridge]]'s ''The Desperate People'', 1963)\n*1965: ''Gl\u00fcck in Frankreich'' \u2014 (based on a story by [[Ernst von Salomon]])\n*1965: ''Acht Stunden Zeit'' \u2014 (based on a play by Charles Ma\u00eetre)\n*1966: ''{{Interlanguage link multi|Melissa (German miniseries)|de|3=Melissa (1966)|lt=Melissa}}'' (TV miniseries) \u2014 (remake of [[Francis Durbridge]]'s ''Melissa'', 1964)\n*1967: ''In Sachen Erzberger gegen Helfferich'' \u2014 (screenplay by [[Axel Eggebrecht]])\n*1967\u20131968: ''[[Sherlock Holmes (1967 TV series)|Sherlock Holmes]]'' (TV series) \u2014 (remake of ''[[Sherlock Holmes (1965 TV series)|Sherlock Holmes]]'', 1965)\n*1968: ''Eine Gefangene bei Stalin und Hitler'' \u2014 (based on ''Under Two Dictators'' by [[Margarete Buber-Neumann]])\n*1969\u20131972: ''[[K\u00f6niglich Bayerisches Amtsgericht]]'' (TV series, 7 episodes)\n*1969: ''Nennen Sie mich Alex'' \u2014 (film about [[Oleg Penkovsky]])\n*1970: ''Theatergarderobe'' (TV series)\n*1971: ''Die Schrott-Story''\n*1971\u20131972: ''F\u00fcnf Tage hat die Woche'' (TV series)\n*1972: ''Nicht Lob \u2013 noch Furcht. Graf Galen, Bischof von M\u00fcnster'' \u2014 (screenplay by [[Luise Rinser]])\n*1972\u20131975: ''{{Ill|Im Auftrag von Madame|de}}'' (TV series, 32 episodes)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0003904|Paul May}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:May, Paul}}\n[[Category:1909 births]]\n[[Category:1976 deaths]]\n[[Category:German television directors]]\n[[Category:German film directors]]\n[[Category:German-language film directors]]\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_May"}
{"title_page": "Andrew Cotter", "text_new": "{{short description|British sports broadcaster}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n'''Andrew Cotter''' (born 20 July 1973) is a [[Scottish people|Scottish]] [[sports presenter|sports broadcaster]] working primarily for the [[BBC]], covering mainly [[golf]] and [[rugby union]], but also [[tennis]], [[Sport of athletics|athletics]] and [[The Boat Race]]<ref>https://www.bbc.com/historyofthebbc/research/the-boat-race</ref><ref> https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/golf/8655617/Rising-star-of-BBC-sports-commentary-Andrew-Cotter-is-not-jack-of-all-trades-...-but-could-be-a-master-of-them.html </ref>.\n\n==Personal life==\nCotter is from [[Troon]] in [[Ayrshire]] and has a degree in French and Philosophy from the [[University of Glasgow]].<ref>http://www.andrewcotter.co.uk/about-andrew/</ref> He played golf for Scottish Schools and Scottish Universities.<ref name=\"BBC pro\">[http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/biographies/biogs/sport/andrewcotter.shtml BBC profile]</ref><ref name=\"CotPuff\">[http://www.andrewcotter.co.uk/biography/ Profile of Andrew Cotter on personal website]</ref> He currently lives in [[Cheshire]].\n\nCotter owns two [[Labrador Retriever|Labrador]] dogs: Olive and Mabel. A video of Cotter commentating his dogs went viral in March 2020, during the [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] shutdown.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Harmon|first=Steph|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2020/apr/10/coronavirus-stars-bbc-sports-commentator-andrew-cotters-dogs-olive-and-mabel-go-viral|title=Coronavirus stars: BBC sports commentator Andrew Cotter's dogs Olive and Mabel go viral|date=2020-04-10|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-15|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Radio===\nCotter started his broadcasting career at [[Scot FM]], a commercial radio station based in [[Edinburgh]], in 1997. In 2000 he moved to London to work at both [[BBC Radio 5 Live]] and [[Sky News]]. It was at [[BBC Radio]] that he began his commentary career, in both rugby and golf covering The [[Six Nations Championship|6 Nations]] and [[Rugby World Cup]] as well as [[The Masters]], [[Open Championship]]<ref> https://www.todaysgolfer.co.uk/news-and-events/tour-news/2016/july1/andrew-cotter-knows-troon-better-than-anyone/ </ref>, [[US Open]], [[PGA Championship]] and [[Ryder Cup]]. At the same time he was presenting sports bulletins across [[BBC Radio]].\n\n===Television===\nCotter\u2019s work in television began in 2001, presenting sports bulletins on [[BBC News 24]]. In 2003 he began commentating on golf for [[BBC]] Television,<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/av/golf/13586680</ref> covering [[The Masters]] and [[Open Championship]]<ref> https://www.scotsman.com/sport/rugby-union/interview-bbcs-andrew-cotter-art-commentating-1473571 </ref>, as well as other events on [[The European Tour]]. That year he also began commentating on [[rugby union]] for [[BBC Sport]], primarily covering The [[6 Nations Championship]].\n\nIn 2008, he began commentating on tennis and is a regular voice at [[The Championships, Wimbledon]] on The [[BBC]].<ref> https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/tennis/wimbledon-commentator-andrew-cotter-firmly-5954200 </ref>\n\nSince 2013, Cotter has been part of BBC Sport\u2019s commentary team for athletics, working on several [[European Athletics]] and [[World Athletics Championships]], as well as [[The Olympic Games]].<ref> https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/proginfo/2016/31/rio-2016-opening-ceremony </ref> He has attended three Olympics, initially as a multi-sport commentator, but since 2016 as part of the athletics team and also as commentator on The Opening and Closing ceremonies.\n\nCotter took over as lead commentator on [[The Boat Race]]<ref>https://www.bbc.com/historyofthebbc/research/the-boat-race</ref>, when it returned to [[BBC]] from [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] in 2011.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/sporteditors/2009/03/boat_race_returning_to_the_bbc_1.html</ref>\n\n\n===Former BBC positions===\n* 2000\u20132004: Commentator on BBC Radio 5 Live covering Golf and Rugby Union\n* 2001\u20132006: Sports presenter on BBC News 24 and BBC World.\n* 2008: Commentated on 2008 Summer Olympic Games for BBC Covering Weightlifting and Modern Pentathlon.\n* 2011: Main BBC Commentator on the [[2011 Australian Open]] tennis\n* 2012: London 2012 Summer Olympics, commentating on Tennis and Canoeing/Kayaking events.\n\n===Current BBC positions===\n* 2002\u2013present: Ryder Cup for Radio 5 Live\n* 2004\u2013present: rugby union commentator for TV on 6 Nations and Autumn Internationals\n* 2004\u2013present: TV golf commentator on Open, Masters, Ryder Cup & Women's Open\n* 2008\u2013present: TV tennis commentator for [[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon]], [[Queen's Club Championships|AEGON Championships]] at [[Queen's Club]] and [[Eastbourne International|AEGON International]] at [[Devonshire Park Lawn Tennis Club|Eastbourne]]\n* 2010\u2013present: Boat Race commentator on Television (replaced by [[Jonathan Legard]] in 2012 and 2015 as the Boat Race clashed with the US Masters Golf)\n* 2013\u2013present: Athletics on TV including at the [[2014 Commonwealth Games]] in [[Glasgow]]\n* 2016 Rio Olympics covering the athletics [[2016 Summer Olympics]] in [[Rio de Janeiro]], [[Brazil]]\n\n===Freelance work===\n* 2011: ESPN Rugby when Nick Mullins was commentating on the Rugby World Cup for ITV\n* 2012: Wheelchair Rugby for Channel 4 Paralympic Coverage\n* 2010\u20132014: Sky Sports Red Button commentary of the Heineken Cup\n* 2014\u2013present: Pool Stage commentator for BT Sport European Rugby Champions Cup & European Rugby Challenge Cup\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cotter, Andrew}}\n[[Category:Tennis commentators]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:BBC sports presenters and reporters]]\n[[Category:Golf writers and broadcasters]]\n[[Category:Scottish rugby union commentators]]\n[[Category:Scottish sports broadcasters]]\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n\n\n{{UK-tv-journalist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British sports broadcaster}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n'''Andrew Cotter''' (born 20 July 1973) is a [[Scottish people|Scottish]] [[sports presenter|sports broadcaster]] working primarily for the [[BBC]], covering mainly [[golf]] and [[rugby union]], but also [[tennis]], [[Sport of athletics|athletics]] and [[The Boat Race]]<ref>https://www.bbc.com/historyofthebbc/research/the-boat-race</ref><ref> https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/golf/8655617/Rising-star-of-BBC-sports-commentary-Andrew-Cotter-is-not-jack-of-all-trades-...-but-could-be-a-master-of-them.html </ref>.\n\n==Personal life==\nCotter is from [[Troon]] in [[Ayrshire]] and has a degree in French and Philosophy from the [[University of Glasgow]].<ref>http://www.andrewcotter.co.uk/about-andrew/</ref> He played golf for Scottish Schools and Scottish Universities.<ref name=\"BBC pro\">[http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/biographies/biogs/sport/andrewcotter.shtml BBC profile]</ref><ref name=\"CotPuff\">[http://www.andrewcotter.co.uk/biography/ Profile of Andrew Cotter on personal website]</ref> He currently lives in [[Cheshire]].\n\nCotter owns two [[Labrador Retriever|Labrador]] dogs: Olive and Mabel. A video of Cotter commentating his dogs went viral in March 2020, during the [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] shutdown.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Harmon|first=Steph|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2020/apr/10/coronavirus-stars-bbc-sports-commentator-andrew-cotters-dogs-olive-and-mabel-go-viral|title=Coronavirus stars: BBC sports commentator Andrew Cotter's dogs Olive and Mabel go viral|date=2020-04-10|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-15|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Radio===\nCotter started his broadcasting career at [[Scot FM]], a commercial radio station based in [[Edinburgh]], in 1997. In 2000 he moved to London to work at both [[BBC Radio 5 Live]] and [[Sky News]]. It was at [[BBC Radio]] that he began his commentary career, in both rugby and golf covering The [[6 Nations]] and [[Rugby World Cup]] as well as [[The Masters]], [[Open Championship]]<ref> https://www.todaysgolfer.co.uk/news-and-events/tour-news/2016/july1/andrew-cotter-knows-troon-better-than-anyone/ </ref>, [[US Open]], [[PGA Championship]] and [[Ryder Cup]]. At the same time he was presenting sports bulletins across [[BBC Radio]].\n\n===Television===\nCotter\u2019s work in television began in 2001, presenting sports bulletins on [[BBC News 24]]. In 2003 he began commentating on golf for [[BBC]] Television,<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/av/golf/13586680</ref> covering [[The Masters]] and [[Open Championship]]<ref> https://www.scotsman.com/sport/rugby-union/interview-bbcs-andrew-cotter-art-commentating-1473571 </ref>, as well as other events on [[The European Tour]]. That year he also began commentating on [[rugby union]] for [[BBC Sport]], primarily covering The [[6 Nations Championship]].\n\nIn 2008, he began commentating on tennis and is a regular voice at [[The Championships, Wimbledon]] on The [[BBC]].<ref> https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/tennis/wimbledon-commentator-andrew-cotter-firmly-5954200 </ref>\n\nSince 2013, Cotter has been part of BBC Sport\u2019s commentary team for athletics, working on several [[European Athletics]] and [[World Athletics Championships]], as well as [[The Olympic Games]].<ref> https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/proginfo/2016/31/rio-2016-opening-ceremony </ref> He has attended three Olympics, initially as a multi-sport commentator, but since 2016 as part of the athletics team and also as commentator on The Opening and Closing ceremonies.\n\nCotter took over as lead commentator on [[The Boat Race]]<ref>https://www.bbc.com/historyofthebbc/research/the-boat-race</ref>, when it returned to [[BBC]] from [[ITV]] in 2011.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/sporteditors/2009/03/boat_race_returning_to_the_bbc_1.html</ref>\n\n\n===Former BBC positions===\n* 2000\u20132004: Commentator on BBC Radio 5 Live covering Golf and Rugby Union\n* 2001\u20132006: Sports presenter on BBC News 24 and BBC World.\n* 2008: Commentated on 2008 Summer Olympic Games for BBC Covering Weightlifting and Modern Pentathlon.\n* 2011: Main BBC Commentator on the [[2011 Australian Open]] tennis\n* 2012: London 2012 Summer Olympics, commentating on Tennis and Canoeing/Kayaking events.\n\n===Current BBC positions===\n* 2002\u2013present: Ryder Cup for Radio 5 Live\n* 2004\u2013present: rugby union commentator for TV on 6 Nations and Autumn Internationals\n* 2004\u2013present: TV golf commentator on Open, Masters, Ryder Cup & Women's Open\n* 2008\u2013present: TV tennis commentator for [[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon]], [[Queen's Club Championships|AEGON Championships]] at [[Queen's Club]] and [[Eastbourne International|AEGON International]] at [[Devonshire Park Lawn Tennis Club|Eastbourne]]\n* 2010\u2013present: Boat Race commentator on Television (replaced by [[Jonathan Legard]] in 2012 and 2015 as the Boat Race clashed with the US Masters Golf)\n* 2013\u2013present: Athletics on TV including at the [[2014 Commonwealth Games]] in [[Glasgow]]\n* 2016 Rio Olympics covering the athletics [[2016 Summer Olympics]] in [[Rio de Janeiro]], [[Brazil]]\n\n===Freelance work===\n* 2011: ESPN Rugby when Nick Mullins was commentating on the Rugby World Cup for ITV\n* 2012: Wheelchair Rugby for Channel 4 Paralympic Coverage\n* 2010\u20132014: Sky Sports Red Button commentary of the Heineken Cup\n* 2014\u2013present: Pool Stage commentator for BT Sport European Rugby Champions Cup & European Rugby Challenge Cup\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cotter, Andrew}}\n[[Category:Tennis commentators]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:BBC sports presenters and reporters]]\n[[Category:Golf writers and broadcasters]]\n[[Category:Scottish rugby union commentators]]\n[[Category:Scottish sports broadcasters]]\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n\n\n{{UK-tv-journalist-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:6 Nations\u2192Six Nations Championship,ITV\u2192ITV (TV network)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andrew_Cotter"}
{"title_page": "Rangpur (fruit)", "text_new": "{{taxobox\n|name = Rangpur<br>''Citrus'' \u00d7 ''limonia''\n|image = Citrus x limonia (2).jpg\n|image_caption = Rangpur fruit\n|regnum = [[Plantae]]\n|unranked_divisio = [[Angiosperms]]\n|unranked_classis = [[Eudicots]]\n|unranked_ordo = [[Rosids]]\n|ordo = [[Sapindales]]\n|familia = [[Rutaceae]]\n|genus = ''[[Citrus]]''\n|species = '''''C.'' \u00d7 ''limonia'''''\n|binomial = ''Citrus'' \u00d7 ''limonia''\n|binomial_authority = [[Pehr Osbeck|Osbeck]]\n|}}\n'''Rangpur''', '''''Citrus'' \u00d7 ''limonia''''' or '''''Citrus reticulata'' \u00d7 ''medica''''', sometimes called the rangpur lime, mandarin lime or lemandarin, is a hybrid between the [[mandarin orange]] and the [[citron]]. It is a [[citrus]] [[fruit]] with a very [[acid]]ic taste and an [[orange (color)|orange]] peel and flesh.\n\n==Common names==\nCommon names for this fruit include rangpur, the word possibly originated in the [[Bengali language]]. Rangpur is also known in the [[Indian subcontinent]] as ''[[Sylhet region|Sylhet]] lime'', ''surkh nimboo'', and ''sharbati''.<ref name=\"ucr\" /> It is known as a ''canton-lemon'' in South China, a ''hime-lemon'' in Japan, as ''lim\u00e3o-capeta'', ''lim\u00e3o-cravo'', ''lim\u00e3o-rosa''  or ''lim\u00e3o-galego'' in Brazil and Portugal (namely in the Azores), and ''mandarin-lime'' in the United States.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://hort.purdue.edu/newcrop/morton/mandarin_lime.html}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n''Citrus'' \u00d7 ''limonia'' was introduced into Florida in the late nineteenth century by Reasoner Brothers of Oneco, which obtained seed from northwestern India.<ref name=\"ucr\">[http://www.citrusvariety.ucr.edu/citrus/rangpur.html U.C. Riverside Citrus Profile: Rangpur - ''Citrus \u00d7 limonia'']</ref> Though often described as a lemon hybrid, genomic analysis has shown it to be an [[F1 hybrid]] of a female citron (''Citrus medica'') and a male mandarin orange (''Citrus reticulata'').<ref name=\"limes and lemons\">{{cite journal | title=Phylogenetic origin of limes and lemons revealed by cytoplasmic and nuclear markers | last1=Curk | first1=Franck | last2=Ollitrault | first2= Fr\u00e9d\u00e9rique | last3=Garcia-Lor | first3= Andres | last4=Luro | first4=Fran\u00e7ois | last5=Navarro | first5=Luis | last6=Ollitrault | first6=Patrick | journal=Annals of Botany | volume=11 | issue=4 | pages=565\u2013583 | year=2016 | doi=10.1093/aob/mcw005 | pmid=26944784 | pmc=4817432 }}</ref><ref name=\"Talon\">{{cite journal|title=Genomics of the origin and evolution of ''Citrus'' | last1=Wu | first1=Guohong Albert | last2=Terol | first2=Javier | last3=Ibanez | first3=Victoria | last4=L\u00f3pez-Garc\u00eda | first4=Antonio | last5=P\u00e9rez-Rom\u00e1n | first5=Estela | last6=Borred\u00e1 | first6=Carles | last7=Domingo | first7=Concha | last8=Tadeo | first8=Francisco R | last9=Carbonell-Caballero | first9=Jose | last10=Alonso | first10=Roberto | last11=Curk | first11=Franck | last12=Du | first12=Dongliang | last13=Ollitrault | first13=Patrick | last14=Roose | first14=Mikeal L. Roose | last15=Dopazo | first15=Joaquin | last16=Gmitter Jr | first16=Frederick G. | last17=Rokhsar | first17=Daniel | last18=Talon | first18=Manuel | journal=Nature | year = 2018 | volume=554 | issue=7692 | pages=311\u2013316 | doi=10.1038/nature25447| pmid=29414943 | doi-access=free }} and Supplement</ref>\n\n==Use==\nRangpurs are highly acidic and can be used as a substitute for [[Lime (fruit)|limes]]. However the name lime in connection with this fruit is misleading, because there are very few similarities between the rangpur and other fruits called limes.\n\nIn 2006, [[Diageo]] introduced a rangpur-flavored version of [[Tanqueray]] [[gin]], known simply as Tanqueray Rangpur.\n\n;Cultivation\n''Citrus'' \u00d7 ''limonia'' is cultivated as an [[ornamental tree]] for planting in [[garden]]s and a container plant on [[patio]]s and [[Terrace (building)|terraces]] in the United States. Outside the U.S. it is used principally as a [[citrus rootstock]], except [[Costa Rica]] where it is also grown commercially and is preferred over lime and lemon.<ref name=\"ucr\"/>\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Rangpurgin.jpg|A bottle of [[Tanqueray]] Rangpur gin\nFile:Citrus x limonia (Osbeck) Lemandrine 001.jpg|''Citrus \u00d7 limonia''' - Rangpur, flower and foliage\nFile:Citrus x limonia (Osbeck) Lemandrine 003.jpg|''Citrus \u00d7 limonia''' - Rangpur, fruit and foliage\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Citrus x limonia}}\n*{{Wikispecies inline|Citrus limonia}}\n{{Citrus|state=collapsed}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1304478}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rangpur (Fruit)}}\n[[Category:Citrus hybrids]]\n[[Category:Flora of India (region)]]\n[[Category:Garden plants of Asia]]\n[[Category:Ornamental trees]]\n[[Category:Lemons]]\n", "text_old": "{{taxobox\n|name = Rangpur<br>''Citrus'' \u00d7 ''limonia''\n|image = Citrus x limonia (2).jpg\n|image_caption = Rangpur fruit\n|regnum = [[Plantae]]\n|unranked_divisio = [[Angiosperms]]\n|unranked_classis = [[Eudicots]]\n|unranked_ordo = [[Rosids]]\n|ordo = [[Sapindales]]\n|familia = [[Rutaceae]]\n|genus = ''[[Citrus]]''\n|species = '''''C.'' \u00d7 ''limonia'''''\n|binomial = ''Citrus'' \u00d7 ''limonia''\n|binomial_authority = [[Pehr Osbeck|Osbeck]]\n|}}\n'''Rangpur''', '''''Citrus'' \u00d7 ''limonia''''' or '''''Citrus reticulata'' \u00d7 ''medica''''', sometimes called the rangpur lime, mandarin lime or lemandarin, is a hybrid between the [[mandarin orange]] and the [[citron]]. It is a [[citrus]] [[fruit]] with a very [[acid]]ic taste and an [[orange (color)|orange]] peel and flesh.\n\n==Common names==\nCommon names for this fruit include rangpur, the word possibly originated in the [[Bengali language]]. Rangpur is also known in the [[Indian subcontinent]] as ''[[Sylhet region|Sylhet]] lime'', ''surkh nimboo'', and ''sharbati''.<ref name=\"ucr\" /> It is known as a ''canton-lemon'' in South China, a ''hime-lemon'' in Japan, as ''lim\u00e3o-capeta'', ''lim\u00e3o-cravo'', ''lim\u00e3o-rosa''  or ''lim\u00e3o-galego'' in Brazil and Portugal (namely in the Azores), and ''mandarin-lime'' in the United States.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://hort.purdue.edu/newcrop/morton/mandarin_lime.html}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n''Citrus'' \u00d7 ''limonia'' was introduced into Florida in the late nineteenth century by Reasoner Brothers of Oneco, which obtained seed from northwestern India.<ref name=\"ucr\">[http://www.citrusvariety.ucr.edu/citrus/rangpur.html U.C. Riverside Citrus Profile: Rangpur - ''Citrus \u00d7 limonia'']</ref> Though often described as a lemon hybrid, genomic analysis has shown it to be an [[F1 hybrid]] of a female citron (''Citrus medica'') and a male mandarin orange (''Citrus reticulata'').<ref name=\"limes and lemons\">{{cite journal | title=Phylogenetic origin of limes and lemons revealed by cytoplasmic and nuclear markers | last1=Curk | first1=Franck | last2=Ollitrault | first2= Fr\u00e9d\u00e9rique | last3=Garcia-Lor | first3= Andres | last4=Luro | first4=Fran\u00e7ois | last5=Navarro | first5=Luis | last6=Ollitrault | first6=Patrick | journal=Annals of Botany | volume=11 | issue=4 | pages=565\u2013583 | year=2016 | doi=10.1093/aob/mcw005 | pmid=26944784 | pmc=4817432 }}</ref><ref name=\"Talon\">{{cite journal|title=Genomics of the origin and evolution of ''Citrus'' | last1=Wu | first1=Guohong Albert | last2=Terol | first2=Javier | last3=Ibanez | first3=Victoria | last4=L\u00f3pez-Garc\u00eda | first4=Antonio | last5=P\u00e9rez-Rom\u00e1n | first5=Estela | last6=Borred\u00e1 | first6=Carles | last7=Domingo | first7=Concha | last8=Tadeo | first8=Francisco R | last9=Carbonell-Caballero | first9=Jose | last10=Alonso | first10=Roberto | last11=Curk | first11=Franck | last12=Du | first12=Dongliang | last13=Ollitrault | first13=Patrick | last14=Roose | first14=Mikeal L. Roose | last15=Dopazo | first15=Joaquin | last16=Gmitter Jr | first16=Frederick G. | last17=Rokhsar | first17=Daniel | last18=Talon | first18=Manuel | journal=Nature | year = 2018 | volume=554 | issue=7692 | pages=311\u2013316 | doi=10.1038/nature25447| pmid=29414943 | doi-access=free }} and Supplement</ref>\n\n==Use==\nRangpurs are highly acidic and can be used as a substitute for [[Lime (fruit)|limes]]. However the name lime in connection with this fruit is misleading, because there are very few similarities between the rangpur and other fruits called limes.\n\nIn 2006, [[Diageo]] introduced a rangpur-flavored version of [[Tanqueray]] [[gin]], known simply as Tanqueray Rangpur.\n\n;Cultivation\n''Citrus'' \u00d7 ''limonia'' is cultivated as an [[ornamental tree]] for planting in [[garden]]s and a container plant on [[patio]]s and [[Terrace (building)|terraces]] in the United States. Outside the U.S. it is used principally as a [[citrus rootstock]], except [[Costa Rica]] where it is also grown commercially and is preferred over lime and lemon.<ref name=\"ucr\"/>\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Rangpurgin.jpg|A bottle of [[Tanqueray]] Rangpur gin\nFile:Citrus x limonia (Osbeck) Lemandrine 001.jpg|''Citrus \u00d7 limonia''' - Rangpur, flower and foliage\nFile:Citrus x limonia (Osbeck) Lemandrine 003.jpg|''Citrus \u00d7 limonia''' - Rangpur, fruit and foliage\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Citrus x limonia}}\n*{{Wikispecies inline|Citrus limonia}}\n{{Citrus|state=collapsed}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1304478}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rangpur (Fruit)}}\n[[Category:Citrus hybrids]]\n[[Category:Flora of Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Flora of India]]\n[[Category:Garden plants of Asia]]\n[[Category:Ornamental trees]]\n[[Category:Lemons]]\n", "name_user": "Declangi", "label": "safe", "comment": "Category:Flora of India (region) - WGSRPD category", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rangpur_(fruit)"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Czech Republic", "text_new": "{{Current disaster|event=pandemic|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Ongoing COVID-19 viral pandemic in the Czech Republic}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Czech Republic\n| map1            = COVID-19 outbreak Czechia per capita cases map.svg\n| legend1         = Confirmed cases per million residents by region\n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Czech Republic]]\n| first_case      = Unknown\n| arrival_date    = 1 March 2020<br/>({{Age in years, months, weeks and days\n | month1 = 03\n | day1   = 1\n | year1  = 2020\n | month2 = \n | day2   = \n | year2  = }} ago)\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], Hubei, China\n| confirmed_cases = 6,838<ref name=\":0\"/>\n| recovery_cases  = 1,559<ref name=\":0\"/>\n| deaths          = 194<ref name=\":0\"/>\n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|https://onemocneni-aktualne.mzcr.cz/covid-19}}\n}}\n\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] saw its first three confirmed cases in the [[Czech Republic]] on 1 March 2020. On 12 March, the government declared a [[state of emergency]], for the first time in the country's modern history for the area of the entire country. On 16 March, the country closed its borders, forbade the entry of foreigners and issued a nationwide curfew. While originally planned until 24 March, the measures were later extended until 1 April<ref name=\"apnews\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radio.cz/en/section/breaking/czech-republic-severely-limits-freedom-of-movement-in-order-to-slow-down-coronavirus-spread|title=Czech Republic goes into quarantine to slow down coronavirus spread|website=Radio Prague International|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref> and then again until the end of State of Emergency<ref name=\"third travel ban\" /> which was extended by the [[Chamber of Deputies of the Czech Republic|Chamber of Deputies]] until 30 April 2020.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.psp.cz/eknih/2017ps/stenprot/043schuz/s043037.htm#h8 |title=P\u010cR, PS 2017 , 43. sch\u016fze, \u010d\u00e1st 37 (7. 4. 2020) |publisher=Psp.cz |date= |accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nCzech Republic started gradual easing of measures from 7 April 2020 onwards.<ref name=\"third travel ban\" /><ref name=\"sports allowed\" />\n\n== Background ==\nOn 12 January 2020, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] was the cause of a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in Wuhan City, Hubei Province, China, which was reported to the WHO on 31 December 2019.<ref name=Elsevier>{{cite web |url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center |title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center |last=Elsevier |date= |website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Reynolds4March2020>{{Cite news |last=Reynolds |first=Matt |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus |title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic? |date=4 March 2020 |work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020 |issn=1357-0978|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Case fatality rate|case fatality ratio]] for COVID-19 has been much lower than [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS of 2003]],<ref name=Imperial13March2020>{{cite web |url= https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/ |title=Crunching the numbers for coronavirus |website=Imperial News|access-date=15 March 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084913/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Gov.ukHCIDDef>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid |title=High consequence infectious diseases (HCID); Guidance and information about high consequence infectious diseases and their management in England |date= |publisher=Government of the United Kingdom |url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200303051938/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> but the [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] has been significantly greater, with a significant total death toll.<ref name=WFSA>{{cite web |url= https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus |title=World Federation Of Societies of Anaesthesiologists \u2013 Coronavirus |date= |website=wfsahq.org|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233527/https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Imperial13March2020/>\n\n==Timeline==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/The Czech Republic medical cases chart}}\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\" style=\"text-align:left; font-size:80%; float:right; clear:right; margin:0 0 0.5em 1em;\"\"\n|+COVID-19 cases in the Czech Republic<ref name=\":0\"/>\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Date\n! colspan=\"2\" | Confirmed\n! colspan=\"2\" | Recovered\n! colspan=\"2\" | Deaths\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Active<br / >cases\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Tested<br/>(Total)\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Detected<br/>ratio\n|-\n! New\n! Total\n! New\n! Total\n! New\n! Total\n|-\n! 28 February\n| 0 || 0\n| 0 || 0\n| 0 || 0\n| 0\n| 193\n| \n|-\n! 29 February\n| 0 || 0\n| 0 || 0\n| 0 || 0\n| 0\n| 200\n| \n|-\n! 1 March\n| 3 || 3\n| 0 || 0\n| 0 || 0\n| 3\n| 211\n| {{#expr:3/(211-200)*100 round 2}}%\n|-\n! 2 March\n|